SIMPLE: negotiation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Negotiation
<hw>Ne*go`ti*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>negotiatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>n⟦eacute⟧gociation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of negotiating; a treating with
another respecting sale or purchase. etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, mercantile business; trading.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who had lost, with these prizes, forty thousand pounds, after
twenty years' <qex>negotiation</qex> in the East Indies.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The transaction of business between nations; the
mutual intercourse of governments by diplomatic agents, in making
treaties, composing difference, etc.; <as>as, the <ex>negotiations</ex>
at Ghent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An important <qex>negotiation</qex> with foreign powers.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Negotiator</ent>⟦br⟧
